    public PurchasingTraining(AppDbContext db, Dictionary<string, int> slugMap) : base(db, slugMap) { }

    public override async Task SeedAsync()
    {
        // ── Overview (Article) ───────────────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Purchasing Overview",
            Slug = "purchasing-overview",
            Summary = "What RFQs are, the request-for-quote lifecycle, inviting vendors, recording responses, awarding a vendor, and how an award generates a Purchase Order.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 6,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 1,
            AppRoutes = """["/purchasing"]""",
            Tags = """["purchasing","rfq","procurement"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Purchasing Overview\n\nThe Purchasing module manages **RFQs** — Requests for Quote. An RFQ is how you ask one or more vendors to quote a price (and terms) for a part you need to buy, compare the responses you get back, and then **award** the work to a vendor. Awarding an RFQ generates a Purchase Order automatically, so the RFQ is the front end of the procurement flow that ends in a PO.\n\nPurchasing connects to two other features. Each RFQ is for a single **Part**, and you invite one or more **Vendors** to quote it. When you award a winning response, the system creates the linked **Purchase Order**.\n\n### What Is an RFQ?\n\nAn RFQ represents a single request to source a part. Each RFQ has:\n- A unique **RFQ #** (auto-generated)\n- A link to exactly one **Part**\n- A **Quantity** you need\n- A **Required Date** (when you need the part)\n- An optional **Response Deadline** (when vendors must respond by)\n- Optional **Description** and **Special Instructions**\n- A **Status** tracking where the RFQ is in its lifecycle\n- A set of **Vendor Responses** — one per invited vendor — each holding that vendor's quote\n\n### RFQ Lifecycle\n\nRFQs move through these statuses:\n\n1. **Draft** — The RFQ has been created but not yet sent to any vendor. This is the initial status. You can still edit it freely.\n2. **Sent** — The RFQ has been sent to one or more vendors using the Send to Vendors action. Each invited vendor gets a response record in Pending status.\n3. **Receiving** — Quotes are coming back. As you record vendor responses, the RFQ reflects that responses are being collected.\n4. **Evaluating** — You are comparing the responses you have received before deciding who to award.\n5. **Awarded** — You have awarded the RFQ to one vendor's response. The award timestamp is recorded and a Purchase Order is generated. This is effectively terminal.\n6. **Cancelled** — The RFQ was cancelled.\n7. **Expired** — The RFQ passed its window without being awarded.\n\n### Inviting Vendors\n\nFrom the RFQ detail, the **Send to Vendors** action opens a multi-select of vendors (it excludes vendors you have already invited). Pick the vendors you want quotes from and send. Each invited vendor gets a vendor response in **Pending** status, and the RFQ moves to Sent. You can invite vendors while the RFQ is in Draft or Sent status.\n\n### Recording Vendor Responses\n\nWhen a vendor quotes back, use the **Record Response** action (available while the RFQ is Sent or Receiving). Pick the vendor (only those with a Pending response appear), then enter the quote: **Unit Price**, **Lead Time (days)**, **Minimum Order Quantity (MOQ)**, **Tooling Cost**, **Quote Valid Until**, and **Notes**. Only the vendor selection is required; every quote field is optional, so you can record a partial quote. Recording a response moves that vendor's response to **Received**.\n\n### Comparing and Awarding\n\nThe vendor responses table shows every invited vendor and their quote side by side so you can compare price, lead time, MOQ, and tooling cost. When you decide, click **Award** on the winning response. Award is available only when the RFQ is not already Awarded, Cancelled, or Expired, and only for a response in **Received** status.\n\nAwarding confirms the choice, then:\n- The RFQ status becomes **Awarded** and the award timestamp is recorded.\n- A **Purchase Order is generated** and linked to the RFQ.\n- The winning response is marked **Awarded** (green); every other response becomes **Not Awarded** (amber).\n- A success message offers a **View PO** link, and the generated PO appears as a link in the RFQ's read-only fields.\n\nAward is a one-way, irreversible action — it is the only button that creates a PO from an RFQ.\n\n### Vendor Response Statuses\n\nEach vendor's response on an RFQ has its own status: **Pending** (invited, no quote yet), **Received** (quote recorded), **Declined** (vendor declined to quote), **Awarded** (this response won), and **Not Awarded** (another response won).\n\n### How Purchasing Connects to Other Features\n\n**Vendors:** You invite vendors to an RFQ, and each vendor's quote lives on a vendor response. Awarding ties the resulting PO to the chosen vendor.\n\n**Purchase Orders:** Awarding an RFQ generates a Purchase Order. The PO is linked back from the RFQ so you can open it directly.\n\n**Parts:** Every RFQ is for one part from the catalog, shown with its part number and description.\n\n### When to Use Purchasing\n\n- When you need to buy a part and want competitive quotes — create an RFQ\n- When you want several vendors to bid — invite multiple vendors with Send to Vendors\n- When quotes come back — record each vendor's response to compare them\n- When you have chosen a winner — award the response to generate the Purchase Order","sections":[]}"""
        });

        // ── Walkthrough ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
